        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>GBP Posts</strong> are updates you publish directly to a Google Business Profile — announcements, offers, events, and product highlights. They appear on the profile in Google Search and Maps, expire after <strong>7 days for standard types</strong>, and contribute to the freshness signal Google uses to judge profile activity. Consistent weekly posting correlates with higher Local Pack visibility and can lift GBP impressions <strong>up to 60%</strong> in a quarter.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Post lifespan</div>
            <div class="tms-value"><span class="http-code-chip warn">7 days</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO · GBP</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ideal cadence</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2-3 per week</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">GBP Posts are the closest thing to a free ad unit on the Google Search results page. Every post that goes live occupies the "Updates" section of your listing and signals to Google that the profile is actively operated.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are GBP Posts?</h2>
        <p>GBP Posts are short-form updates published directly through the Google Business Profile dashboard. Once published, they appear on the profile in Google Search and Maps under the "Updates" or "Offers" tab, and Google may surface them alongside the main listing card. They combine text (up to 1,500 characters), an image, and an optional CTA button — "Book," "Order online," "Learn more," "Sign up," "Call now."</p>
        <p>Four post types exist:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Update</strong> — general announcements, news, or content promotion</li>
          <li><strong>Offer</strong> — discounts, deals, promotions with a start and end date</li>
          <li><strong>Event</strong> — dated activities with a title, description, and event window</li>
          <li><strong>Product</strong> — spotlight on a specific product from the profile catalog</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why the freshness signal matters</div>
          <p>Google's Local Pack algorithm rewards profiles that show activity. A profile without a post in the last week reads as inactive. Consistent weekly posting has been observed to lift GBP impressions <strong>up to 60% in a single quarter</strong> in multi-location retail case studies.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why GBP Posts matter</h2>
        <p>For local businesses, GBP Posts do four things no other free channel can:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Free real estate on the SERP.</strong> Posts appear on the listing in Search and Maps without any paid placement — the closest thing to a free ad unit on the Google results page.</li>
          <li><strong>Freshness signal.</strong> Weekly posting tells Google the profile is actively operated, which correlates with higher Local Pack rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>Direct action.</strong> Every post can carry a CTA — Book, Order, Sign up — turning a passive listing view into a lead capture surface.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitor gap.</strong> Most competing profiles post rarely, if at all. A consistent posting cadence puts you above 80% of local competitors instantly.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How GBP Posts work</h2>
        <p>Posts flow through a simple lifecycle: draft in the dashboard, publish, live for 7 days for standard types, then archive under the profile's Updates tab.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># The GBP Post lifecycle</span><br>
          Draft <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Add image + text + CTA<br>
          Publish <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Live on profile in <span class="uf-new">Search + Maps</span><br>
          Day 1-7 <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Displayed prominently in Updates section<br>
          Day 8+ <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Archived under Updates tab (still accessible)<br>
          <span class="uf-status">Freshness signal continues only while a recent post exists</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Text length and structure</h3>
        <p>Up to 1,500 characters, but the first 100-150 characters carry the most weight because they show above the fold on mobile. Front-load the key message and the CTA.</p>

        <h3>Image requirements</h3>
        <p>Recommended 1200x900 pixels, JPG or PNG. Landscape images crop better than square in the post preview. Use real business images — same rules as the main photo library.</p>

        <h3>CTA button options</h3>
        <p>Book, Order online, Buy, Learn more, Sign up, Call now, Get offer. Match the CTA to the post type — offers pair with "Get offer," events pair with "Sign up" or "Learn more."</p>

        <h2 id="types">GBP Post types compared</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
