        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real GBP Post examples</h2>
        <p>Three case studies where GBP Posts moved measurable numbers.</p>

        <h3>1. Denver plumbing company — weekly Update cadence</h3>
        <p>Published one Update post per week covering common seasonal issues — pipe insulation in winter, sprinkler system checks in spring. Each post carried a "Call now" CTA. Delivered 3-5 additional calls per week attributable directly to the posts appearing on the listing.</p>

        <h3>2. Multi-location restaurant chain — 12-location rollout</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Q1 rollout across 12 locations</span><br>
          Cadence <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">2 posts per location per week</span><br>
          Content mix <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Menu highlights + weekly offers<br>
          <span class="uf-status">GBP impressions +60% in Q1</span>
        </div>

        <h3>3. Independent hair salon — competitor pattern</h3>
        <p>The competing salon posting weekly outranked salons that did not. After adopting a 3-post-per-week cadence with product spotlights and stylist showcases, the salon closed the ranking gap in 8 weeks and pulled ahead on the "hair salon near me" pack within a month more.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">GBP Posts vs GBP Photos — where each fits</h2>
        <p>Both feed freshness signals. Posts add CTAs and copy; photos add pure visual trust. Best profiles do both.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use GBP Posts when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You want a CTA button next to the content</li>
              <li>Announcing offers, events, or updates</li>
              <li>Building weekly freshness cadence</li>
              <li>Promoting specific dated actions</li>
              <li>Testing offer copy against engagement</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use GBP Photos when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Filling required category slots</li>
              <li>Building the general photo library</li>
              <li>Adding visual trust without dated copy</li>
              <li>Signaling freshness at a longer cadence (monthly)</li>
              <li>No CTA needed — just visual</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for GBP Posts in 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Publish 2-3 posts per week minimum.</strong> Posts expire after 7 days. Weekly is the floor; 2-3 keeps the profile visibly active.</li>
          <li><strong>Front-load the message.</strong> First 100-150 characters show above the fold on mobile. Lead with the offer or hook.</li>
          <li><strong>Match CTA to intent.</strong> Book for services, Get offer for deals, Sign up for events. A mismatched CTA hurts click-through.</li>
          <li><strong>Use a real business image.</strong> Same rules as the main photo library. Landscape crops better than square.</li>
          <li><strong>Batch and schedule.</strong> Draft a month of posts in one sitting and schedule with theStacc or Publer to remove the weekly reminder burden.</li>
          <li><strong>Track by post type.</strong> Compare offer clicks vs update clicks vs event signups. Double down on what performs.</li>
          <li><strong>Include a location keyword.</strong> "Denver plumber" in the post copy signals relevance to Google, though it does not replace the profile's category signal.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — one post, then months of silence</div>
          <p>The freshness signal decays after seven days. A single post from six months ago hurts more than never posting at all, because the profile shows a stale "last updated" timestamp. Commit to weekly or do not start.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common GBP Post mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Long, corporate copy.</strong> The first 100 characters do the work. Everything after is buried on mobile.</li>
          <li><strong>Stock imagery.</strong> Detectable and hurts trust. Use real business photos.</li>
          <li><strong>No CTA button.</strong> Skipping the CTA means the post generates impressions but not actions.</li>
          <li><strong>Posting once a month.</strong> Below the freshness threshold. Weekly minimum.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring offer end dates.</strong> Expired offers still on the profile look sloppy. Remove or refresh.</li>
          <li><strong>Copy-pasted across locations.</strong> Multi-location businesses should localize copy — city name, location-specific detail — even if the offer is the same.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps</h2>
        <p>theStacc's Local SEO module schedules GBP Posts weeks in advance, generates first-draft copy from a brief, and tracks impressions and clicks by post type. For multi-location businesses, the module publishes localized variants to every profile in one workflow — the ongoing cadence stops depending on someone remembering to log into GBP.</p>

